<body>

<nav>
  <div class="wrap" style="width: 100%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between;">
    <a href="index.html" class="nav-brand">
      SQL to C#
      <span class="nav-pill">Ch 05</span>
    </a>
    <ul class="nav-links">
      <li><a href="index.html">← All Chapters</a></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</nav>

<div class="wrap">
  <header class="chapter-header">
    <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 05</div>
    <h1>SELECT → .Select() — Projections</h1>
    <p class="chapter-desc">Select only the columns you need. Projections reduce data transfer, memory use, and query cost.</p>
  </header>

  <div class="in-this-chapter">
    <h3>In This Chapter</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Basic column selection: choosing which columns to fetch</li>
      <li>Computed columns and aliases for on-the-fly transformations</li>
      <li>SELECT DISTINCT and removing duplicates</li>
      <li>Conditional logic with CASE and ternary operators</li>
      <li>Projection targets: anonymous types, DTOs, and records</li>
      <li>Nested aggregations with let binding</li>
      <li>Verifying generated SQL with .ToQueryString()</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- SECTION 01: Basic Column Selection -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-num">01</div>
    <h2>Basic Column Selection</h2>

    <p class="section-text">
      Selecting specific columns is more efficient than SELECT *. The database reads fewer pages, transfers less data, and your app uses less memory.
    </p>

    <div class="triple-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT Name, Email, Phone
FROM Customers;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-method">
        <span class="code-label">Method Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => new {
    c.Name,
    c.Email,
    c.Phone
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-query">
        <span class="code-label">Query Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await (from c in customers.AsNoTracking()
              select new {
                c.Name,
                c.Email,
                c.Phone
              })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      Both C# approaches create anonymous types with only the properties you need. EF Core translates both to identical SQL that selects only those columns.
    </p>

    <div class="key-insight">
      <strong>Why It Matters</strong>
      <p>On a 20-column table needing 3 columns, projection reduces result volume by ~85%. Less I/O, smaller network packets, less memory—all from one simple .Select() call.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 02: Computed Columns and Aliases -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-num">02</div>
    <h2>Computed Columns and Aliases</h2>

    <p class="section-text">
      Transform data at query time, not in your application. SQL uses AS for aliases, LINQ uses property assignment. The database does the work—it's far faster.
    </p>

    <div class="triple-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT
  OrderId,
  Quantity,
  UnitPrice,
  Quantity * UnitPrice AS Total,
  Quantity * UnitPrice * 0.9 AS Discounted
FROM OrderItems;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-method">
        <span class="code-label">Method Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await items
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(i => new {
    i.OrderId,
    i.Quantity,
    i.UnitPrice,
    Total = i.Quantity * i.UnitPrice,
    Discounted = i.Quantity
      * i.UnitPrice * 0.9m
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-query">
        <span class="code-label">Query Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await (from i in items.AsNoTracking()
              select new {
                i.OrderId,
                i.Quantity,
                i.UnitPrice,
                Total = i.Quantity * i.UnitPrice,
                Discounted = i.Quantity
                  * i.UnitPrice * 0.9m
              })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      String operations work the same way:
    </p>

    <div class="triple-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT
  FirstName,
  LastName,
  CONCAT(FirstName, ' ', LastName) AS FullName,
  LEN(Email) AS EmailLength
FROM Users;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-method">
        <span class="code-label">Method Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await users
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(u => new {
    u.FirstName,
    u.LastName,
    FullName = $"{u.FirstName} "
      + u.LastName,
    EmailLength = u.Email.Length
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-query">
        <span class="code-label">Query Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await (from u in users.AsNoTracking()
              select new {
                u.FirstName,
                u.LastName,
                FullName = $"{u.FirstName} "
                  + u.LastName,
                EmailLength = u.Email.Length
              })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      Handle NULLs with COALESCE / ?? operator:
    </p>

    <div class="code-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT
  CustomerId,
  COALESCE(MiddleName, '') AS Middle,
  ISNULL(Phone, 'No phone') AS Phone
FROM Customers;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">C#</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => new {
    c.CustomerId,
    Middle = c.MiddleName ?? "",
    Phone = c.Phone ?? "No phone"
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-insight">
      <strong>Push to Database</strong>
      <p>Computing in SQL means parallel processing of millions of rows. Computing in C# means fetching everything first. Always push computation down with .Select().</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 03: SELECT DISTINCT -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-num">03</div>
    <h2>SELECT DISTINCT — Removing Duplicates</h2>

    <p class="section-text">
      DISTINCT eliminates duplicate rows. It's expensive (requires sorting or hashing) but necessary when you need unique values. Apply it at the database level, not after fetching.
    </p>

    <div class="triple-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT DISTINCT City
FROM Customers
ORDER BY City;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-method">
        <span class="code-label">Method Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => c.City)
  .Distinct()
  .OrderBy(city => city)
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-query">
        <span class="code-label">Query Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await (from c in customers.AsNoTracking()
              select c.City)
  .Distinct()
  .OrderBy(city => city)
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      DISTINCT on multiple columns:
    </p>

    <div class="triple-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT DISTINCT City, Country
FROM Customers
ORDER BY Country, City;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-method">
        <span class="code-label">Method Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => new { c.City, c.Country })
  .Distinct()
  .OrderBy(x => x.Country)
  .ThenBy(x => x.City)
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-query">
        <span class="code-label">Query Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await (from c in customers.AsNoTracking()
              select new { c.City, c.Country })
  .Distinct()
  .OrderBy(x => x.Country)
  .ThenBy(x => x.City)
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-insight">
      <strong>Filter Early</strong>
      <p>SELECT DISTINCT with WHERE first, then DISTINCT. Filtering 10,000 rows down to 500 before DISTINCT is far cheaper than DISTINCT on 10,000 rows.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 04: CASE → Conditional Logic -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-num">04</div>
    <h2>CASE Expressions and Conditional Projections</h2>

    <p class="section-text">
      SQL's CASE and C#'s ternary operator (? :) both compute conditional values at the database level. Use these to categorize or transform data without application logic.
    </p>

    <div class="triple-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT
  Name,
  Age,
  CASE
    WHEN Age >= 18 THEN 'Adult'
    WHEN Age >= 13 THEN 'Teenager'
    ELSE 'Child'
  END AS AgeCategory
FROM Users;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-method">
        <span class="code-label">Method Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await users
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(u => new {
    u.Name,
    u.Age,
    AgeCategory = u.Age >= 18
      ? "Adult"
      : u.Age >= 13
        ? "Teenager"
        : "Child"
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-query">
        <span class="code-label">Query Syntax</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await (from u in users.AsNoTracking()
              select new {
                u.Name,
                u.Age,
                AgeCategory = u.Age >= 18
                  ? "Adult"
                  : u.Age >= 13
                    ? "Teenager"
                    : "Child"
              })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      Multiple conditions:
    </p>

    <div class="code-comparison">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT
  OrderId,
  OrderTotal,
  CASE
    WHEN OrderTotal > 1000 THEN 'Premium'
    WHEN OrderTotal > 500 THEN 'Standard'
    WHEN OrderTotal > 100 THEN 'Small'
    ELSE 'Minimal'
  END AS Category
FROM Orders;</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">C#</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await context.Orders
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(o => new {
    o.OrderId,
    o.OrderTotal,
    Category = o.OrderTotal > 1000
      ? "Premium"
      : o.OrderTotal > 500
        ? "Standard"
        : o.OrderTotal > 100
          ? "Small"
          : "Minimal"
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-insight">
      <strong>Keep It Simple</strong>
      <p>EF translates comparisons, arithmetic, and string methods in .Select(). Calling custom C# functions breaks translation. Keep expressions database-translatable.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 05: Projection Targets -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-num">05</div>
    <h2>Projecting to DTOs, Records, and Anonymous Types</h2>

    <p class="section-text">
      Choose your projection target based on scope: anonymous types for local use, DTOs for reusable data transfer, records for immutable value semantics. EF generates identical SQL for all three.
    </p>

    <p class="section-text">
      Anonymous types (one-off, local):
    </p>

    <div class="code-single">
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">Anonymous Type</span>
        <pre><code>// Compiler-generated, not reusable outside this method
var result = await context.Customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => new {
    c.Id,
    c.Name,
    OrderCount = c.Orders.CountAsync()
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      DTOs (reusable classes):
    </p>

    <div class="code-comparison">
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">DTO Definition</span>
        <pre><code>public class CustomerSummary
{
  public int Id { get; set; }
  public string Name { get; set; }
  public int OrderCount { get; set; }
}</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">Project to DTO</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await context.Customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => new CustomerSummary {
    Id = c.Id,
    Name = c.Name,
    OrderCount = c.Orders.CountAsync()
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      Records (immutable):
    </p>

    <div class="code-comparison">
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">Record Definition</span>
        <pre><code>public record CustomerSummary(
  int Id,
  string Name,
  int OrderCount
);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">Project to Record</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await context.Customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => new CustomerSummary(
    c.Id,
    c.Name,
    c.Orders.CountAsync()
  ))
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-insight">
      <strong>Performance: All Identical</strong>
      <p>EF generates the same SQL regardless of target type. Choose by scope: anonymous for local queries, DTO for API responses, record for immutable data.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 06: Nested Aggregations -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-num">06</div>
    <h2>Nested Aggregations with let</h2>

    <p class="section-text">
      Use LINQ's let keyword to compute intermediate values in complex projections. Makes the select clause cleaner and easier to read.
    </p>

    <div class="code-comparison">
      <div class="code-block csharp-method">
        <span class="code-label">Without let (Less Clear)</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await context.Customers
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(c => new {
    c.Id,
    c.Name,
    OrderCount = c.Orders.CountAsync(),
    TotalSpent = c.Orders.SumAsync(o => o.Total ?? 0)
  })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block csharp-query">
        <span class="code-label">With let (More Readable)</span>
        <pre><code>var result = await (from c in context.Customers.AsNoTracking()
              let count = c.Orders.CountAsync()
              let total = c.Orders.SumAsync(o => o.Total ?? 0)
              select new {
                c.Id,
                c.Name,
                OrderCount = count,
                TotalSpent = total
              })
  .ToListAsync(cancellationToken);</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="code-single">
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">Generated SQL (Both Produce This)</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT
  c.Id,
  c.Name,
  COUNT(o.Id) AS OrderCount,
  COALESCE(SUM(o.Total), 0) AS TotalSpent
FROM Customers AS c
LEFT JOIN Orders AS o ON c.Id = o.CustomerId
GROUP BY c.Id, c.Name;</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-insight">
      <strong>One Level Deep</strong>
      <p>Shallow nested aggregations (counts, sums over one related table) work well. Deep nesting (3+ levels) can cause N+1 queries or cartesian products. Flatten when possible.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 07: Verify Generated SQL -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-num">07</div>
    <h2>Understanding Generated SQL</h2>

    <p class="section-text">
      Always inspect what SQL EF generates. Use .ToQueryString() (EF Core 5.0+) or enable query logging to verify your LINQ translates efficiently.
    </p>

    <div class="code-comparison">
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">LINQ Query</span>
        <pre><code>var query = context.Products
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Where(p => p.Category == "Electronics")
  .Select(p => new {
    p.Id,
    p.Name,
    p.Price
  });

string sql = query.ToQueryString();
Console.WriteLine(sql);</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">Generated SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT p.Id, p.Name, p.Price
FROM Products AS p
WHERE p.Category = N'Electronics';</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      With computed columns:
    </p>

    <div class="code-comparison">
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">LINQ</span>
        <pre><code>var query = context.OrderItems
  .AsNoTracking()
  .Select(oi => new {
    oi.OrderId,
    Subtotal = oi.Quantity * oi.UnitPrice,
    WithTax = (oi.Quantity * oi.UnitPrice) * 1.1m
  });

string sql = query.ToQueryString();</code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="code-block sql">
        <span class="code-label">Generated SQL</span>
        <pre><code>SELECT
  oi.OrderId,
  (oi.Quantity * oi.UnitPrice) AS Subtotal,
  ((oi.Quantity * oi.UnitPrice) * 1.1) AS WithTax
FROM OrderItems AS oi;</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="section-text">
      Enable automatic logging:
    </p>

    <div class="code-single">
      <div class="code-block csharp">
        <span class="code-label">DbContext Query Logging</span>
        <pre><code>var options = new DbContextOptionsBuilder<AppDbContext>()
  .UseSqlServer(connectionString)
  .LogTo(
    message => Console.WriteLine(message),
    LogLevel.Information
  )
  .Build();</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-insight">
      <strong>Never Assume</strong>
      <p>Verify every complex .Select() with .ToQueryString(). Look for: SELECT *, missing WHERE, unexpected JOINs, unintended GROUP BY. These are signs translation failed or is inefficient.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- KEY TAKEAWAYS -->
  <div class="key-takeaways">
    <h3>Key Takeaways</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Use .Select() to project only needed columns. Reduces I/O, network, and memory.</li>
      <li>Compute in SQL (at database), not in C#. Use .Select() for arithmetic, string ops, and null coalescing.</li>
      <li>DISTINCT is expensive. Apply at DB level in .Select().Distinct(), not in-memory after fetching.</li>
      <li>CASE (SQL) = ternary (C#). Entity Framework translates nested ternaries to SQL CASE.</li>
      <li>Anonymous types for local one-offs, DTOs for reusable data transfer, records for immutable structures.</li>
      <li>let keyword simplifies complex query syntax projections by breaking calculations into steps.</li>
      <li>Always use .ToQueryString() to verify generated SQL. Never assume translation is efficient.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

